title: For Sale:  Used Beretta 1201 FP 12GA police version semi-auto shotgun
postcontent: This auction is for a used but very nice shape Beretta 1201FP 12GA police version semi-auto shotgun. This shotgun, developed in the late 1980s or early 1990s by the famous Italian arms manufacturing company Pietro Beretta, is, basically, an upgrade over the preceding model, Beretta 1200. The 1201 was manufactured in two versions, 1201F,intended for hunting and sporting, and the 1201FP, intended for police and other such duties. Interestingly enough, the 1201 is extremely similar to the BenelliM1 Super 90 shotgun, and had the same recoil-operated semiautomatic action,developed and patented by Benelli. The production of the Beretta 1201 shotguns had been completed. Since the basic action of the 1201 is similar to such of the Benelli M1 shotgun,for the technical description please refer to the appropriate article at this site. The 1201FP was available with polymer furniture and stock, either with classic or pistol grip. Since the recoil spring is located in the buttstock,this shotgun cannot be fitted with the folding buttstock. The 1201FP can be found with either ghost-ring (large aperture diopter) or open rifle-type rearsights, and with the blade front sight We are willing look at trade offers. We offer Layaway with 10% down and 3 months for the balance. Please add 3% for credit cards

title: For Sale:  .458 SOCOM 16" AR Upper
postcontent:
The .458 SOCOM was created, based on requirements by the Special Operations Command (SOCOM), for Task Force Ranger and some elements of Delta and Seals, that were operating in Somalia (Mogadishu) in the late 90's early 2000's. These special ops soldiers were asking for a better "knock down, one shot, one kill" ability because their M4's, calibred in 5.56, were not effective as a CQB take down round (they needed multiple shots to knock down and/or kill the Somali's). The requirement also required the upgraded caliber to be compatible with the current M4 platform. The end result was... (1) a .458 caliber bullet fired from a different barrel that was used in the current M4 upper receiver,...(2) development of a different bolt because of the size of the .458 round, but, maintain the same bolt carrier, and...(3) the ejection port on the current M4 upper receiver would have to be enlarged for the ejection of the larger piece of brass. These three items are the only difference between a standard AR 15 and the .458 SOCOM. The standard M16 / AR15 lower receiver is to be used with this upper, and was not changed at all. 

Place this upper receiver next to a 5.56 upper receiver and visually there is no difference. The difference becomes apparent only when you squeeze the trigger. At that time all hell breaks loose as you unleash a 300gr bullet, with a muzzle velocity of 1840 fps and 2100 ft lbs of energy towards that feral pig that has been bothering your farm animals. This round, with that much energy, will stop a 300lb feral pig in its tracks. One of the pictures shows three .458 SOCOM 300gr bullets next to a 5.56 SS109 62gr bullet.

***If you are interested in purchasing this upper please email to receive more pictures as ArmsList only allows me 3 pictures***

***This sale is for the complete upper assembly in the picture(s) only***

Your AR 15 lower receiver will attach to, and fire, this 458 SOCOM upper. With the addition of this upper to your collection, you will now have two different calibers (.458 and 5.56/.223) that you can shoot. Just move your lower receiver back and forth........

The upper receiver, barrel, gas block, gas tube, compensator and BCG is from Tromix. The hand guard is T-6061 anodized aluminum, 15" quad rail which allows a full floating barrel. This is a very quality build and has been test fired to ensure all areas of functionality work as required.

The .458 SOCOM bullets will feed into regular AR magazines. A 30 round AR magazine will hold 10 .458 SOCOM rounds as a single stack. Please note that the blue tip round that is pictured can be used "only" in a metal magazine because of the guide edge inside the polymer magpul magazines. The flat nose bullets can be used in all AR magazines.......This is important to know. 

Be advised that the ammo is expensive, and, this is not for "plinkers" (unless you have a lot of money for ammo). I urge you to look up all aspects of this very capable, but very manly, self defense tool. I have built two 16" barreled SOCOM's and one 10.5" pistol. 

Please no trades or low ball offers as the price is very reasonable. Please be respectful.

Thank you for looking at my build.

title: For Sale:  Buyers Beware of AR500 Body Armor (Shot Holes Through it)
postcontent:
I had purchased a set of this Ar500 armor from the Ar500 company and everything here what I had mentioned and posted here is the legitimate truth. I decided to test this out at 20 and 30 yards. Using a 5.56 rounds at it and this was the result. Then had used a 7.62x51 rounds both times at the other plate and penetrated the holes through it.
One bullet shot from both distances. This is absolutely ridiculous and should not have bought this I regret it now and now decided to warn others before buying from them. It is not worth it. I would not trust my life behind this product. This was not intended to downgrade them or anything just warning others through my negative experiences with this. They fraud the public and their clients by saying they are Military however Military has never used or approved of them. If anything I remembered we used them for target practices out on the range than anything else.
Do not waste you're time, resources or money on this product. I've regret doing spending my money on this. Their company deserves to be shut down, I've heard from other sources how they had a negative experience with AR500 armor as well!

Keep in mind that Level III plates ARE NOT rated for 5.56, they are only rated for 7.62 NATO @ 2800 fps. Since the 5.56 round is much faster than that it can defeat the plate. 

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QrWtgyFQ8LU

CMMG 5.56 NATO .223 Rem. Complete M4 Barreled Upper Assembly 16" Chrome Lined Barrel WASP Finish

W.A.S.P. Treated Barrel (Weapon Armament Surface Protection) is a salt bath ferritic nitrocarburizing surface conversion process or more commonly referred to as nitriding. The nitriding conversion is applied to the barrel inside and out, along with the front sight base on our LE rifles and uppers. Nitriding offers improved wear, abrasion, and corrosion resistance when compared to hard chrome lining or phosphating. 
Unlike chrome lining, where the chrome is built up on the surface, nitriding converts the surface without the risk of dimensional build up. CMMG Pioneered the use of this nitriding process on AR barrels and has been using it for many years.

I have a nee in box Pulsar Phantom G2+ 3X50 Night Vision Riflescope. I'd like a new toy so I'm looking for a good trade. Open to a lot. Would love a USO optic or Vortex Razor Gen 2 or high end 1911

The Phantom takes into account all the requirements for modern night hunting. Utilising a military-style design and offering maximum functionality, the Phantom is an obvious choice for anyone who demands the highest quality and impeccable reliability. It is fully weatherproofed, thanks to a nitrogen filled optical channel and waterproofing to IPX6, and can be used anywhere. Arctic ice fields or desert sands, humid tropical forests or harsh Siberian taiga – the Phantom is ready to do its job regardless of weather conditions. The body of the Phantom is made of highly durable glass-filled plastic. The bodyshell design and high grade intensifier tubes ensure shockproofing to heavy calibres, including 9.3x62, 9.3x74 and 375H&H. The Gen 2+ tube has Automatic Brightness Control (ABC) and, coupled with the high quality, wide-aperture lens, provides a sharp and clear picture. The high light gain, combined with the built-in IR - Illuminator, allows hunting even in situations of critically low night illumination (down to 10-4 lx – overcast starlight). The fast start-up function (the sight is “On” only while pressing a button) is very useful for making quick assessments. The problem of choosing a reticle has also been solved effectively. With the Phantom, you can choose the most suitable reticle configuration and change it by simply pressing a button (the Phantom with the Mil-Dot reticle is also available). The voltage stabilization system eliminates reticle shift even with an almost discharged battery. All main controls are on top of the body simplifying accessibility. These and other useful features make the Phantom one of the most interesting and promising new recruits to the class of elite night vision riflescopes.
